 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">1</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">Surface gravity {g}_{s}=\tfrac{G{M}_{p}}{{R}_{p}^{2}} can be calculated from the mass Mp and radius Rp of a rocky planet, or directly by combining the depth of transit with the amplitude of radial velocity (Equation (, 16: #apjaa6218eqn17))</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">2</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">CMF can be determined from Equation (, 1: #apjaa6218eqn1)</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">3</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">CRF can be estimated as \sqrt{\mathrm{CMF}}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">1</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">In the core, the gravity g increases linearly with radius from 0 at the center to gs (surface value) at the CMB (core-mantle boundary): {g}_{\mathrm{core}}(r)={g}_{s}\left(\tfrac{r}{{R}_{\mathrm{core}}}\right)\propto r</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">2</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">In the mantle, g stays constant: {g}_{\mathrm{mantle}}(r)={g}_{s}=\mathrm{const}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">1</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">hydrostatic equilibrium (force balance) equation: \begin{equation*} \begin{align*} \begin{eqnarray}&amp;&amp;\displaystyle \frac{{dP}}{{dr}}=-\displaystyle \frac{{Gm}\rho }{{r}^{2}}=-g\rho \end{eqnarray} \end{align*} \tag{ 2 } \end{equation*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">2</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">mass conservation equation: \begin{equation*} \begin{align*} \begin{eqnarray}&amp;&amp;\displaystyle \frac{{dm}}{{dr}}=4\pi {r}^{2}\rho.\end{eqnarray} \end{align*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\tag{ 3 }</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\end{equation*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">1</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">For Earth, CMF{}_{\oplus } = 0.325 and CRF{}_{\oplus }=\tfrac{3480\,\mathrm{km}}{6371\,\mathrm{km}} = 0.546. So CRF{}_{\oplus }^{2}={0.546}^{2}=0.298, which is ~9% smaller than 0.325</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">2</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">For Kepler-93b, numerical calculations in (,: #apjaa6218bib14) give CMF{}_{{\rm{K}}93{\rm{b}}} = 0.278 and CRF{}_{{\rm{K}}93{\rm{b}}}=0.493. So CRF{}_{{\rm{K}}93{\rm{b}}}^{2} = 0.243, which is ~12% smaller than 0.278</subfield>
  <subfield code="h">Zeng et al.</subfield>
